{{Redirect|Venus's girdle|the marine lifeform|Ctenophora}} {{Refimprove|date=September 2015}} [[File:Moon and red blue haze.jpg|thumb|[[Moon]] seen through the Belt of Venus. Note that the full Moon is near the centre of the field of view, which means that the Sun must be behind the camera, just below the horizon.]] The '''Belt of Venus''', '''Venus's Girdle''', or '''antitwilight arch''' is an [[atmospheric phenomenon]] visible shortly before [[sunrise]] or after [[sunset]], during [[civil twilight]], when a pinkish glow extending roughly [[horizontal coordinate system|10–20°]] above the horizon surrounds the observer.
In a way, the Belt of Venus is actually [[alpenglow]] visible above the horizon during twilight, near the [[antisolar point]]. Like [[alpenglow]], the [[backscatter]] of reddened [[sunlight]] also creates the Belt of Venus. Unlike alpenglow, the sunlight [[refracted]] by the fine [[particulates]] that cause the rosy arch of the Belt hovers high in the atmosphere and persists long after sunset or before sunrise.
As twilight progresses, the glow is separated from the horizon by the dark band of [[Earth's shadow]], or "dark segment." The arch's light pink color is due to the [[backscatter]] of reddened light from the rising or setting [[Sun]]. A very similar effect can be seen during a total [[lunar eclipse]]. The [[zodiacal light]], which is caused by the [[diffuse reflection]] of sunlight from the [[interplanetary dust]] in the [[Solar System]], is also a similar phenomenon.
The name of the phenomenon alludes to the ''cestus'', a girdle or breast-band, of the Ancient Greek goddess [[Aphrodite]], customarily equated with the Roman goddess [[Venus (mythology)|Venus]]. Since the greatest elongation (separation) between Venus and the Sun is only about 46 degrees, the [[planet]] [[Venus]], even when visible, is never located opposite the sun and hence is never located in the Belt of Venus.
==Gallery== <gallery mode=packed> File:ALMA and Chajnantor at Twilight.jpg|[[Atacama Large Millimeter Array|ALMA]] and [[Chajnantor]] at [[twilight]]. Lying between the two groups of antennas are the [[Earth's shadow]] and Belt of Venus phenomena.<ref>{{cite news|title=ALMA and Chajnantor at Twilight|url=http://www.eso.org/public/images/potw1402a/|accessdate=18 January 2014|newspaper=ESO Picture of the Week}}</ref> File:Full moon rising near Linz, Austria.JPG|Full moon rising near [[Linz]], Austria. Observed through the Belt of Venus. File:Belt of Venus, Harbour Lüderitz (Namibia).jpg|''Belt of Venus'' seen from [[Lüderitz Bay]] in [[Namibia]] (2017) File:Belt_of_venus_from_plane.jpg|Belt of Venus at {{convert|42000|ft|m}} File:Seattle Belt of Venus.jpg|Belt of Venus photographed over a [[Green Lake (Seattle)|lake in Seattle, Washington]]. </gallery>
